    "text": "Since R(0) # 0 and k ≥ 2, we conclude that the greatest power of x dividing P\"(x) is 1k-2. But P(x) = e(x)P\" (x), and so x' divides Q(x). We deduce (since @ is quadratic) that Q(x) is a constant C times x2; in fact, C = 1/(n(n-1)) by inspection of the leading-degree terms of P(x) and P\" (x).",
